\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 12. R. rugosus} Campd., {\i Monogr. Rumex }113 (1819) ({\i R. ambiguus }Gren.). Stems 50-160 cm, erect, stout. Basal leaves up to 15 × 10 cm, pale green, somewhat fleshy when alive, very thin when dry, (1½-)2-4 times as long as wide, ovate-oblong, rounded at the apex, with deflexed basal lobes; cauline leaves decreasing slightly upwards, the uppermost sessile, triangular, with a broadly cordate base, tapering towards the apex. Panicle rather lax, the branches repeatedly branched. Valves 3-4 mm. Nut c. 2 mm, dark brown, shiny. 2n = 14(female), 15(male).{\i  Origin unknown; cultivated as a vegetable} ({\i Sorrel}){\i  and established here and there as an escape}.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Known only from cultivation. It has been treated by some authors as a variant or subspecies of {\b 11}, to which vegetatively it bears a close resemblance, although the repeatedly branched inflorescence and the slightly smaller valves are more similar to those of {\b 13}.
\par

